'''''Heavy Metal Islam''''' is a 2008 non-fiction book by [[Mark LeVine]], a professor of [[Middle East]] history.<ref>{{cite web |url        =https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/20/books/review/Hampton-t.html |title =Rock the Casbah  |last =Hampton |first =Howard |date =July 20, 2008 |website =The New York Times |accessdate= June 14, 2013}}</ref> LeVine details the growth of [[heavy metal music]] in the Middle Eastern countries [[Morocco]], [[Egypt]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Lebanon]], [[Iran]] and [[Pakistan]] as he travels within those countries for five years.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://articles.latimes.com/2008/jul/17/entertainment/et-book17 |title    =Heavy metal uprising |last =Appleford |first =Steve |date =July 17, 2008 |website =Los Angeles Times |accessdate = June 14, 2013}}</ref> The book not only is just about his travels and heavy metal music, but was also meant as a promotional tool for his companion album.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Nonfiction-review-Heavy-Metal-Islam-3275410.php |title =Nonfiction review: 'Heavy Metal Islam' |last =McEvers |first =Kelly |date =July 28, 2008 |website =San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate =June 14, 2013}}</ref>

