The '''Hunzibs''' are an indigenous people of [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]] living in three villages in the [[Tsuntinsky District]] in the upper regions of the [[Avar-Koisu river]] area. They have their own language, [[Hunzib language|Hunzib]], and primarily follow [[Sunni Islam]], which reached the Hunzib people around the 8th or 9th century. The only time that the Hunzibs were counted as a distinct ethnic group in the Russian Census was in 1926, when 105 people reported to be ethnic Hunzibs. Subsequently, they were listed as [[Avar people (Caucasus)|Avars]] in the Russian Censuses. In 1967, it was estimated that there were about 600 ethnic Hunzibs (E. Bokarev).

