{{third-party|date=May 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}
The '''International Federation of Air Line Pilots' Associations''' (IFALPA) is a worldwide association of national pilots' associations. IFALPA was founded in 1948 and is based in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada.

== History ==
After the end of the [[Second World War]] as international [[civil aviation]] began to re-establish itself, pilots around the world realized that their associations could not protect them across national boundaries.){{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Furthermore, they did not have a voice at the newly formed [[International Civil Aviation Organization]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} At a meeting in London in April 1948 a conference of pilot associations was held that formed the International Federation of Air Line Pilots' Associations.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} IFALPA was located in the UK from 1948 to 2012. In 2012 the Federation established its headquarters in Montreal, Canada, the global Civil Aviation Decision Making Hub, and is located near ICAO.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

== Membership ==
In 1976 the IFALPA represented 54,000 pilots in their Member Associations in 60 countries. By 2015, that number had grown to over 100,000 pilots in over 100 countries.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

== Connections with ICAO ==
IFALPA has a number of standing committees in regulatory, industrial and safety/technical areas. It also has permanent membership on a number of ICAO Panels and Task Forces to provide pilot input into regulations, design criteria, [[Air traffic management|Air Traffic Management]] and Airport requirements just to name a few.<ref>[http://www.ifalpa.org/about-us/our-history.html Our History]</ref><ref>A. Percy Coldrick and Philip Jones. ''The international directory of the trade union movement'' New York Macmillan, 1979 {{ISBN|978-0333212509}} pp.210, 213</ref>

