'''Limani''' is a town in the [[Far North Region (Cameroon)|Far North Region]] of [[Cameroon]], on the border with [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Limani / Limani, Extreme-Nord, Cameroon, Africa | work = Traveling Luck | accessdate = 2015-01-06 | url = http://travelingluck.com/Africa/Cameroon/Extreme-Nord/_2229413_Limani.html }}</ref>
In 2014, the town was caught up in the [[Boko Haram]] conflict.<ref>{{Cite episode | publisher = [[Voice of America]] | credits = Moki Edwin Kindzeka (Director) | title = Cameroon Army Kills 116 Suspected Boko Haram Militants | work = News / Africa | accessdate = 2015-01-06 | date = 2014-12-19 | url = http://www.voanews.com/content/cameroon-army-kills-suspected-boko-haram-militants/2565529.html }}</ref> In October 2014, Boko Haram fighters entered Limani and [[Amchide]], another border town, killing at least 30 civilians. The [[Cameroonian Armed Forces|Cameroonian Army]] reported 107 Boko Haram members were killed in the fighting that ensued.<ref>{{Cite news | last = AFP | title = Cameroon kills 107 Boko Haram fighters accused of mass murder | work = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | accessdate = 2015-01-05 | date = 2014-10-18 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/nigeria/11171197/Nigerias-missing-schoolgirls-to-be-released-after-ceasefire-deal.html }}</ref> On 28 December 2014, Cameroonian troops repelled simultaneous Boko Haram raids into the towns of Limani, Amchide, [[Makary, Cameroon|Makari]], [[Guirvidig]], [[Waza National Park|Waza]] and [[Achigachia]], all located in Cameroon's Far North region.<ref name=AmER>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/29/us-nigeria-violence-cameroon-idUSKBN0K70PL20141229|title=Cameroon says fights off Boko Haram attacks, kills 41 militants|work=Reuters|date=29 December 2014|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref>
