{{Other uses|Pomeranian (disambiguation)}} The '''Pomeranians''' ({{lang-de|Pomoranen}}; {{lang-csb|Pòmòrzónie}}; {{lang-pl|Pomorzanie}}) were a group of [[West Slavs|West Slavic]] [[tribe]]s who lived along the shore of the [[Baltic Sea]] between the mouths of the [[Oder]] and [[Vistula]] Rivers (the latter [[Farther Pomerania]] and [[Pomerelia]]). They spoke the [[Pomeranian language]] belonging to the [[Lechitic languages|Lechitic]] branch of the [[West Slavic languages|West Slavic language family]]. [[File:West slavs 9th-10th c..png|thumb|400px|Several ethnic groups of West Slavs between 9th–10th centuries]] [[File:Gerson Without land.jpg|thumb|400px|''Without land. Pomeranians driven by the Germans to the Baltic Islands (Expulsion of Pomeranians in the 11th century)'' by [[Wojciech Gerson]], 1888, [[National Museum, Szczecin|National Museum]] in [[Szczecin]]]]
The name ''Pomerania'' comes from [[Slavic languages|Slavic]] ''po more'', which means "Land at the Sea".<ref>[http://www.pommersches-landesmuseum.de/kulturreferat-fuer-pommern/aufgaben/aufgaben.html ''Der Name Pommern (po more) ist slawischer Herkunft und bedeutet so viel wie „Land am Meer“.''] (Pommersches Landesmuseum, German)</ref>
==Overview== The Pomeranian tribes formed after the 6th century, when as a result of the Slavic migration, groups of Slavs populated the area, parts of which were formerly inhabited for some time by [[Germanic tribes]], such as the [[Goths]] and the [[Rugians]] etc.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
From the late 10th century, the [[Piast dynasty|Piast]] dukes of [[Poland during the Piast dynasty|Poland]] tried to incorporate the Pomeranians into their realm and they succeeded several times. The Pomeranians were nevertheless always able to regain their independence. In the course of the 12th century, the non-Christian Pomeranians faced continuous pressure from their expanding Christian neighbours [[Denmark]], [[Poland]], and the [[Duchy of Saxony|Saxon]] dukes of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. In 1121 they were again subdued by the Polish duke [[Bolesław III Wrymouth]], who had Pomerania [[Christianization|Christianized]] by the German missionary [[Otto of Bamberg]].
At the same time the Pomeranian Prince [[Wartislaw I, Duke of Pomerania|Wartislaw I]] conquered the former [[Lutici]] lands west of the Oder. After his successors from the [[House of Pomerania|House of Griffins]] were defeated by the Saxons at the 1164 [[Battle of Verchen]], they accepted the overlordship of Duke [[Henry the Lion]]. The Pomeranian lands were eventually divided, with the Western parts entering the Holy Roman Empire as the [[Duchy of Pomerania]] in 1181, and the Eastern part consisting of [[Pomerelia]] under the [[Samborides]] came under the influence of Poland and, from 1309 onwards, the [[Teutonic Order]].
After the [[Germanization]] of Pomerania resulting from the medieval [[Ostsiedlung]], many Pomeranians were slowly and gradually assimilated and discontinued the use of their Slavic language and culture. The direct descendants of Pomeranians include: * [[Kashubians]], who speak the [[Kashubian language]] * [[Slovincians]] * [[Kociewiacy]] * [[Borowiacy]] * [[West Pomerania|Western Pomeranians]], who speak [[Low German Language|Low German]] or [[Standard German]] * [[Farther_Pomerania|Eastern Pomeranians]], who were [[Expulsion of Germans from Poland|expelled from Pomerania in 1945]] and settled in various parts of Germany and speak either local dialects or [[Standard German]]
==See also== * [[Conversion of Pomerania]] * [[Kashubian-Pomeranian Association]] * [[Pomeranian culture]] * [[Polish tribes]] * [[Early history of Pomerania]] * [[List of Medieval Slavic tribes]]
